This paper is about generative models, specifically Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) and Variational AutoEncoders (VAEs), and their ability to learn a probability model from data. The paper discusses the limitations of GANs in computing sample likelihoods due to the lack of an explicit probability model, which is a common problem in machine learning and falls under the category of statistical inference. Therefore, the most likely sub-category for this paper is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), cs.CV (Computer Vision), cs.IT (Information Theory), and cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
